          </div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Local SDBQL Queries</h2>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          The Rust client supports <strong>full SDBQL query execution</strong> against local data, even when completely offline.
          This is powered by the <code class="text-violet-400">sdbql-core</code> crate, which provides a storage-independent query engine
          that works with SQLite, RocksDB, or any custom data source.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-violet-900/10 rounded-xl p-5 border border-violet-500/20 mb-8">
          <div class="flex items-start">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb text-violet-400 mt-1 mr-3"></i>
            <div>
              <h4 class="text-violet-400 font-bold mb-1">Why This Matters</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                Unlike simple key-value lookups, full SDBQL support means you can run complex queries with filters, sorts,
                aggregations, and joins - all locally. Your application logic doesn't need to change between online and offline modes.
              </p>
            </div>
